<article>
    <h1>4&#xD;&#xA;LEARN TO KNIT</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201223/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-23"><time>2020-12-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE LIVING WELL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The repet­i­tive and rhyth­mic mo­tions of knit­ting is the key to feel­ing re­laxed.</p>
    <p>But “do not ex­pect it to be im­me­di­ately re­lax­ing like go­ing into a spa”, said founder of knit­ting and cro­chet stu­dio Knotty Bic­sie, Ms Betsy Toh. “One has to learn to knit in­de­pen­dently first be­fore en­joy­ing its ther­a­peu­tic ef­fects,” she said. Then, you can zone out and al­low mus­cle mem­ory to do the work.</p>
    <p>Ms Toh con­ducts classes for learn­ers aged 13 and older at her stu­dio in Ubi. Gen­er­ally, knit­ters make wear­ables such as cardi­gans, sweaters, scarves, vests or items such as ta­ble run­ners, cush­ion cov­ers and blan­kets.</p>
    <p>She said: “The repet­i­tive na­ture of knit­ting can be med­i­ta­tive and when done alone in peace, one can even ex­pe­ri­ence a sooth­ing drift of the mind into some­thing of a trance state.”</p>

